🛠 RFC-002: Mathematical Definition of the Traversable Medium Field (TMF-MEDIUM-v0.1)
Status: Draft / Request for Comments
Author: Mingrong Zhao (with AI engineering collaborator)
License: AGPL-3.0
Target Audience: Perception Engineers, Robotics Researchers, Applied Mathematicians

1. Objective
This RFC provides the formal mathematical foundation for the Traversable Medium in TMF. It defines how the physical world is represented as a continuous field rather than discrete objects, enabling deterministic, auditable, and physics-grounded decision making.

2. Core Philosophy
Instead of modeling the environment as “obstacles + free space + semantics”, TMF models it as a unified traversable medium whose boundaries naturally emerge as non-traversable regions.

3. Mathematical Definition
Definition 1: Traversable Medium Field
The environment at time $  t  $ is represented as a time-varying scalar + vector field:
$$M(\mathbf{x}, t) = \left\{ \theta(\mathbf{x}, t),\ \mu(\mathbf{x}, t),\ R(\mathbf{x}, t),\ C(\mathbf{x}, t) \right\}$$
Where:

$  \mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^3  $ (or $  \mathbb{R}^2  $ for 2.5D simplified cases)
$  \theta(\mathbf{x}, t) \in [0, \pi/2]  $: Surface normal angle relative to gravity (slope)
$  \mu(\mathbf{x}, t) \in [0, 1.5]  $: Friction coefficient
$  R(\mathbf{x}, t) \in [0, +\infty)  $: Medium resistance (combines roughness, compliance, vegetation density, etc.)
$  C(\mathbf{x}, t) \in [0, 1]  $: Confidence / certainty of the measurement

Definition 2: Traversability Function
For a specific robot/vehicle type with dynamics $  D  $, we define a binary traversability mask:
$$T_D(M(\mathbf{x}, t)) = 
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if traversable under dynamics } D \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}$$
Example traversability condition (wheeled vehicle):
$$T_D(\mathbf{x}, t) = 1 \quad \text{iff} \quad 
\theta(\mathbf{x}, t) < \theta_{\max}(D) \ \land \ 
\mu(\mathbf{x}, t) > \mu_{\min}(D) \ \land \ 
R(\mathbf{x}, t) < R_{\max}(D)$$

4. Radius Abrupt Mutation Detection (Core Innovation)
Definition 3: Radius Mutation Operator
Let $  r(\mathbf{x}, \phi, t)  $ be the measured distance to the medium boundary along ray direction $  \phi  $.
The Spatial-Medium Radius Abrupt Mutation at point $  \mathbf{x}  $ is defined as:
$$\Delta r(\mathbf{x}, \phi, t) = \left| r(\mathbf{x}, \phi, t) - r(\mathbf{x} + \delta \cdot \mathbf{d}, \phi, t) \right|$$
where $  \mathbf{d}  $ is the direction of motion.
A point is flagged as a potential anomaly / release point if:
$$\Delta r(\mathbf{x}, \phi, t) > \tau_{\text{mutation}}(D, v)$$
This geometric method detects sudden changes in medium continuity (occlusions, emerging objects, sensor ghosts) without relying on semantic classification.

5. Binary Mask Fusion (BMM)
Physical mask $  P(\mathbf{x}, t) = T_D(M(\mathbf{x}, t))  $
Semantic mask $  S(\mathbf{x}, t)  $ (from existing perception system)
Final decision mask:
$$F(\mathbf{x}, t) = P(\mathbf{x}, t) \otimes S(\mathbf{x}, t)$$
where $  \otimes  $ denotes element-wise multiplication (Binary Mask Multiplication).
This ensures:

If physics says impossible → decision is 0 (hard constraint)
Physics allows → semantic rules can still veto


6. Representation Recommendations

Short-term: 2.5D grid + property layers (efficient)
Medium-term: Voxel grid or Octree with attached properties
Long-term: Continuous implicit field (e.g., neural SDF with explicit physical parameters — hybrid white-box)


7. Open Questions for Community

What is the optimal spatial discretization for real-time performance?
How to best propagate uncertainty $  C(\mathbf{x}, t)  $ through the mutation detection?
How to handle dynamic objects within the medium field (moving vehicles, pedestrians)?
Best practices for sensor fusion to estimate $  \{\theta, \mu, R\}  $?


